two thirds of all active players in the game have spent.

252
00:14:23,890 --> 00:14:25,231
But non-spenders aren't driven out

253
00:14:25,231 --> 00:14:29,154
because that still means a third of people

254
00:14:29,154 --> 00:14:32,116
have played the game for a year and a half without spending.

255
00:14:34,710 --> 00:14:37,791
Most of them spend, some people spend pretty quickly.

256
00:14:37,791 --> 00:14:40,573
About 18% of people make their first purchase

257
00:14:40,573 --> 00:14:42,814
on the day of install, and about half

258
00:14:42,814 --> 00:14:44,635
have made their first purchase within a week

259
00:14:44,635 --> 00:14:45,115
of installing the game.

260
00:14:45,115 --> 00:14:46,396
But after that, it takes a long time to go up.

261
00:14:46,396 --> 00:14:47,196
And at a month in, 30% of the people

262
00:14:47,196 --> 00:14:48,317
who are going to purchase have not yet purchased.

263
00:14:48,317 --> 00:14:48,917
And even six months in.

264
00:14:59,312 --> 00:15:01,534
These graphs are not yet at 100%.

265
00:15:01,534 --> 00:15:04,676
People are still making their first purchase,

266
00:15:04,676 --> 00:15:07,257
even people who are going to go on to spend $500 or more.

267
00:15:07,257 --> 00:15:11,860
As you would expect, the biggest spenders

268
00:15:11,860 --> 00:15:14,581
do spend a little bit earlier and a little bit faster

269
00:15:14,581 --> 00:15:16,543
than lesser spenders.

270
00:15:16,543 --> 00:15:17,903
But there's not really a big difference.

271
00:15:17,903 --> 00:15:19,444
People are, a lot of big spenders

272
00:15:19,444 --> 00:15:21,025
are taking their time before they

273
00:15:21,025 --> 00:15:22,026
make their first purchase.

274
00:15:24,562 --> 00:15:26,504
And they're spending gradually over time.

275
00:15:26,504 --> 00:15:31,307
So this breaks all of the spenders out into deciles

276
00:15:31,307 --> 00:15:34,550
by the average amount that they've spent,

277
00:15:34,550 --> 00:15:41,035
and then looks at their spending by time in the game.

278
00:15:41,035 --> 00:15:44,838
And you can see, especially the first and second deciles,

279
00:15:44,838 --> 00:15:47,580
that their investment in the game is really, really gradual.

280
00:15:47,580 --> 00:15:50,582
They're spending kind of the same amount every month

281
00:15:50,582 --> 00:15:50,862
steadily.

282
00:15:52,297 --> 00:15:54,378
It's a little hard to see what some of the lower deciles

283
00:15:54,378 --> 00:15:58,599
are doing here, just because the top ones are so big.

284
00:15:58,599 --> 00:16:01,621
So here in this next slide, I'm taking away the top two.

285
00:16:01,621 --> 00:16:05,142
And you can see that that gradual investment is still

286
00:16:05,142 --> 00:16:10,344
happening just at a slightly less steep angle

287
00:16:10,344 --> 00:16:11,884
and with a lower amount.

288
00:16:11,884 --> 00:16:15,506
The only groups that don't rise significantly over time

289
00:16:15,506 --> 00:16:18,026
are the bottom deciles, where people are spending $20 or less.

290
00:16:18,026 --> 00:16:21,188
And most of those are just making one purchase and done.

291
00:16:25,693 --> 00:16:28,414
So how do you spend $5,000 in a game?

292
00:16:28,414 --> 00:16:35,238
Now I'm gonna look at one individual case of a big spender.

293
00:16:35,238 --> 00:16:37,940
This big spender is a 40-year-old Californian

294
00:16:37,940 --> 00:16:40,061
whose primary game is an action RPG.

295
00:16:40,061 --> 00:16:43,623
It's single player in a social environment

296
00:16:43,623 --> 00:16:44,744
with a lot of skill-based leveling

297
00:16:44,744 --> 00:16:47,325
and multiple class paths that give him

298
00:16:47,325 --> 00:16:49,406
a strong feeling of progress.

299
00:16:49,406 --> 00:16:51,908
There's guilds and co-op multiplayer,

300
00:16:51,908 --> 00:16:53,869
PVP and tournaments that they participate in.

301
00:16:54,202 --> 00:16:57,124
And they play four to six days a week,

302
00:16:57,124 --> 00:16:59,765
play more than 1,000 times lifetime.

303
00:16:59,765 --> 00:17:02,526
And they play and spend in other games.

304
00:17:02,526 --> 00:17:06,488
But 90% of money and time is going into just this one game.

305
00:17:06,488 --> 00:17:08,929
So you can see that that fits the sort

306
00:17:08,929 --> 00:17:12,690
of prototypical stereotype of the big spenders

307
00:17:12,690 --> 00:17:14,431
that we've talked about up to this point.

308
00:17:17,689 --> 00:17:19,490
What do they actually spend on?

309
00:17:19,490 --> 00:17:20,991
So in 2014, they spent about $7,500,

310
00:17:20,991 --> 00:17:23,792
$2,200 on consumables, $1,800 for skill upgrades,

311
00:17:23,792 --> 00:17:25,173
some miscellaneous things, and then

312
00:17:25,173 --> 00:17:31,497
the bulk of their money going towards competitive multiplayer,

313
00:17:31,497 --> 00:17:36,781
tournament skilled wars, PVP, that kind of thing.

314
00:17:36,781 --> 00:17:38,922
So a little bit more about this big spender.

315
00:17:38,922 --> 00:17:39,042
It's me.

316
00:17:47,635 --> 00:17:50,357
And a little bit more about this big spender.

317
00:17:50,357 --> 00:17:52,539
I'm not spending it on a game.

318
00:17:52,539 --> 00:17:53,800
I'm spending it on figure skating.

319
00:17:53,800 --> 00:17:54,260
So how does that work?

320
00:17:54,260 --> 00:17:59,985
Well, believe it or not, there's actually

321
00:17:59,985 --> 00:18:03,768
an amazing parallel between the structure

322
00:18:03,768 --> 00:18:06,710
of competitive figure skating and a game.

323
00:18:06,710 --> 00:18:10,233
This has been the structure for the US Figure Skating

324
00:18:10,233 --> 00:18:13,216
Association since like 60 years, 70 years.

325
00:18:13,216 --> 00:18:15,658
But they may as well have invented gamification.

326
00:18:15,658 --> 00:18:15,818
So.

327
00:18:17,119 --> 00:18:21,302
It's a single-player sport in a social environment.

328
00:18:21,302 --> 00:18:23,985
So, individual sport done in a shared session.

329
00:18:23,985 --> 00:18:29,189
So, I skate at the Yerba Buena rink that's kind of right on top of the conference center right now

330
00:18:29,189 --> 00:18:34,073
with other people who I get to know well and become friends with.

331
00:18:34,073 --> 00:18:37,976
If this makes me slightly cooler, one of them is occasionally Brian Boitano.

332
00:18:40,211 --> 00:18:41,192
who is a very nice guy.

333
00:18:41,192 --> 00:18:45,375
There's skill-based leveling, multiple class paths,

334
00:18:45,375 --> 00:18:50,579
so there's five different classes in which you compete

335
00:18:50,579 --> 00:18:53,201
and can test up and level up.

336
00:18:53,201 --> 00:18:56,864
I'm progressing along the moves in the field,

337
00:18:56,864 --> 00:19:01,367
basic skills tests, as well as singles, freestyle.

338
00:19:01,367 --> 00:19:01,587
And I am...

339
00:19:04,718 --> 00:19:08,319
I've tested through three levels on moves in the field

340
00:19:08,319 --> 00:19:11,220
and on two levels on freestyle and working

341
00:19:11,220 --> 00:19:13,261
to level up on both.

342
00:19:13,261 --> 00:19:18,142
And I do this by learning new skills, achievements,

343
00:19:18,142 --> 00:19:19,122
and then testing in the test session.

344
00:19:19,122 --> 00:19:22,703
So, say, an example might be a sit-spin or a flip-jump

345
00:19:22,703 --> 00:19:24,263
or something like that.

346
00:19:24,263 --> 00:19:25,684
There's guilds and co-op multiplayer.

347
00:19:30,337 --> 00:19:33,599
So I'm a member of the skating club of San Francisco.

348
00:19:33,599 --> 00:19:36,761
I'm also a member of a synchronized skating team.

349
00:19:36,761 --> 00:19:38,102
And believe me, there's nothing cool about that.

350
00:19:38,102 --> 00:19:41,684
That's the picture of me in that red sequined vest

351
00:19:41,684 --> 00:19:43,306
with something really strange in my hair.

352
00:19:43,306 --> 00:19:45,687
That's my synchronized skating team.

353
00:19:45,687 --> 00:19:47,348
There's also ice dance in Paris, but I don't do that.

354
00:19:48,957 --> 00:19:51,098
And there's competitive multiplayer.

355
00:19:51,098 --> 00:19:54,179
So there's frequent competitions

356
00:19:54,179 --> 00:19:57,359
organized by age, level, and mode.

357
00:19:57,359 --> 00:19:59,940
And points are also tallied for clubs and rinks.

358
00:19:59,940 --> 00:20:02,720
And that pressure is actually very real

359
00:20:02,720 --> 00:20:04,681
and very significant, and is the reason why

360
00:20:04,681 --> 00:20:07,301
in that picture there to the right,

361
00:20:07,301 --> 00:20:09,742
I'm dressed like a B-52.

362
00:20:09,742 --> 00:20:11,742
We were hosting a competition at my rink,

363
00:20:11,742 --> 00:20:13,143
and the rink manager wanted.

364
00:20:13,483 --> 00:20:19,708
all of the good skaters to compete in as many events as possible so we would earn more points.

365
00:20:19,708 --> 00:20:24,112
And she made me do this group routine in this particular outfit.

366
00:20:24,112 --> 00:20:27,635
And the good news is that we did win that trophy and she was happy.

367
00:20:31,229 --> 00:20:36,812
So, what, you know, I gave all these sort of game equivalents to my spending.

368
00:20:36,812 --> 00:20:43,775
So, the consumables was my ice time, so just going to my daily session costs about $11.

369
00:20:43,775 --> 00:20:46,116
I do that almost every day. That adds up.

370
00:20:46,116 --> 00:20:50,638
The skilled upgrades are my private lessons.

371
00:20:50,638 --> 00:20:54,380
I take a $135 half hour lesson every week.

372
00:20:54,380 --> 00:20:55,660
That ends up being about $1,800 a year.

373
00:20:57,820 --> 00:21:01,624
There's some miscellaneous costs for equipment and costumes.

374
00:21:01,624 --> 00:21:06,088
But the big bulk of money is going to competition fees

375
00:21:06,088 --> 00:21:08,811
and travel to get to competitions.

376
00:21:08,811 --> 00:21:10,212
And even with $7,500, I definitely

377
00:21:10,212 --> 00:21:12,895
haven't hit my max spend.

378
00:21:12,895 --> 00:21:15,878
I'm actually participating in relatively few competitions,

379
00:21:15,878 --> 00:21:18,020
because I have to travel so much for Congregate already.

380
00:21:18,839 --> 00:21:23,083
And while I'm naturally thrifty, I'm happy to spend this money.

381
00:21:23,083 --> 00:21:26,546
I love skating enough that a 10% increase in my skills

382
00:21:26,546 --> 00:21:28,308
is worth 10x the cost.

383
00:21:28,308 --> 00:21:30,830
When I make this comparison, people

384
00:21:30,830 --> 00:21:34,273
will often dismiss it as being fundamentally different

385
00:21:34,273 --> 00:21:35,514
because skating is exercise.

386
00:21:36,338 --> 00:21:39,521
I can resell my skates, et cetera.

387
00:21:39,521 --> 00:21:41,903
Skating is good for my health, but you can see here

388
00:21:41,903 --> 00:21:46,146
that most of my spend is going to skill progression

389
00:21:46,146 --> 00:21:49,029
and competition, and that's exactly the same things

390
00:21:49,029 --> 00:21:50,910
that you spend on in game.

391
00:21:50,910 --> 00:21:53,792
Nothing, well, except for the actual ice time,

392
00:21:53,792 --> 00:21:56,935
nothing that's listed here has any resale value

393
00:21:56,935 --> 00:22:00,017
or does any good for my health.

394
00:22:00,017 --> 00:22:01,719
Even the equipment is really services

395
00:22:01,719 --> 00:22:03,500
like skate sharpening and my locker.

396
00:22:05,515 --> 00:22:08,318
And my larger point here is that games are hobbies,

397
00:22:08,318 --> 00:22:10,159
and people spend a lot on their hobbies.

398
00:22:10,159 --> 00:22:13,762
So an example would be a weekly golfer

399
00:22:13,762 --> 00:22:17,104
could easily spend $10,000 a year on greens fees,

400
00:22:17,104 --> 00:22:21,268
and golf clubs, lessons, going to the driving range.

401
00:22:22,256 --> 00:22:25,879
somebody's an amateur guitarist, while they might not spend much day to day,

402
00:22:25,879 --> 00:22:32,223
the few that I've known tend to obsess about collecting guitars and, you know,

403
00:22:32,223 --> 00:22:35,945
will go visit shops that have guitars that they like that they can't afford

404
00:22:35,945 --> 00:22:36,686
just to sort of touch and see them.

405
00:22:38,227 --> 00:22:42,211
and usually end up spending more than they really want to on guitars.

406
00:22:42,211 --> 00:22:45,514
Going to eat in restaurants adds up very quickly if you do it weekly,

407
00:22:45,514 --> 00:22:47,356
especially in San Francisco.

408
00:22:47,356 --> 00:22:52,100
And baseball fans, season tickets, a visit to spring training,

409
00:22:52,100 --> 00:22:54,443
that can be 5,000 between them pretty quickly.

410
00:22:56,211 --> 00:23:00,093
Even something like your aunt does, like quilting.

411
00:23:00,093 --> 00:23:01,814
Materials get expensive pretty quickly,

412
00:23:01,814 --> 00:23:03,374
and it's nicer to use nice materials,

413
00:23:03,374 --> 00:23:06,556
so people will spend on that.

414
00:23:06,556 --> 00:23:08,617
A really good sewing machine is going to cost $5,000,

415
00:23:08,617 --> 00:23:12,179
and if you're doing it all the time, you're going to want that.

416
00:23:12,179 --> 00:23:15,280
Even something that seems like it would be really cheap,

417
00:23:15,280 --> 00:23:17,701
relatively like running.

418
00:23:18,442 --> 00:23:23,665
somebody who becomes a competitive runner is likely to start spending money.

419
00:23:23,665 --> 00:23:26,826
You're going to go through shoes pretty quickly,

420
00:23:26,826 --> 00:23:27,947
and at $100, $150 a pop,

421
00:23:27,947 --> 00:23:31,469
you can spend $500 on shoes and clothes quite easily.

422
00:23:31,469 --> 00:23:36,252
Especially once you start competing, race fees and travel to races,

423
00:23:36,252 --> 00:23:38,893
it adds up just the way my figure skating does.

424
00:23:41,170 --> 00:23:43,171
So how did I get started on this path?

425
00:23:43,171 --> 00:23:47,333
And I think looking at sort of the long term pattern

426
00:23:47,333 --> 00:23:49,955
of my spin kind of explains a lot about

427
00:23:49,955 --> 00:23:52,796
sort of the psychology and how things work.

428
00:23:52,796 --> 00:23:56,298
So I started skating back in 2004.

429
00:23:57,695 --> 00:24:00,156
looking for an alternative exercise,

430
00:24:00,156 --> 00:24:03,357
immediately fell in love, started taking group lessons,

431
00:24:03,357 --> 00:24:06,918
and I bought skates.

432
00:24:06,918 --> 00:24:11,319
And in 2005 and early 2006, my spend was accelerating.

433
00:24:11,319 --> 00:24:15,401
Then in June of 2006, my brother and I started Congregate,

434
00:24:15,401 --> 00:24:19,602
and suddenly I had neither money nor time.

435
00:24:19,602 --> 00:24:21,163
We were going without salaries.

436
00:24:21,163 --> 00:24:23,183
And so there's about a two-year period

437
00:24:23,183 --> 00:24:25,144
where I was barely skating and barely spending at all.

438
00:24:26,205 --> 00:24:26,786
things stabilized by 2009.

439
00:24:26,786 --> 00:24:28,888
And I went back to sort of the trend line

440
00:24:28,888 --> 00:24:30,009
that I'd been on before.

441
00:24:30,009 --> 00:24:30,990
In 2010, we sold Kongregate to GameStop.

442
00:24:30,990 --> 00:24:35,374
And I used some of that money to buy custom skates.

443
00:24:35,374 --> 00:24:37,676
And then they're made by the same people who

444
00:24:37,676 --> 00:24:38,517
make them for Brian Boitano.

445
00:24:38,517 --> 00:24:41,300
So again, they're very cool.

446
00:24:41,300 --> 00:24:43,562
And I'm still using those from five years ago.

447
00:24:51,270 --> 00:24:53,051
It was a good investment.

448
00:24:53,051 --> 00:24:55,912
And then I started competing and joined the SYNC team.

449
00:24:55,912 --> 00:24:59,373
It jumped a lot last year when I went to compete at my first nationals.

450
00:24:59,373 --> 00:25:01,394
It was in Massachusetts in April.

451
00:25:01,394 --> 00:25:08,856
I'm probably the only person who has ever combined a trip to PAX East and adult skating nationals.

452
00:25:08,856 --> 00:25:12,938
And this coming year, I expect that I'm going to spend even more.

453
00:25:15,460 --> 00:25:19,087
guesstimating somewhere around $12,000.

454
00:25:19,087 --> 00:25:20,069
When I turned 40 last year,

455
00:25:20,069 --> 00:25:22,073
my family gave me a really, really lovely gift

456
00:25:22,073 --> 00:25:25,860
of a trip to the Dorothy Hamill Fantasy Skate Camp.

457
00:25:26,774 --> 00:25:37,101
It was awesome, and I'm likely to go back and spend a week with great coaches skating for a week again.

458
00:25:37,101 --> 00:25:47,328
And I could really easily see spending, say, $20,000 in a year if I did both adult nationals and the big international competition in Germany,

459
00:25:47,328 --> 00:25:49,570
work with a choreographer, do things like that.

460
00:25:50,391 --> 00:25:52,794
So I don't know that I would do that sort of regularly,

461
00:25:52,794 --> 00:25:55,597
but I can very much see that happening

462
00:25:55,597 --> 00:25:58,401
and feel that it would be rational.

463
00:25:58,401 --> 00:25:59,963
You know, the choices that I'm making here

464
00:25:59,963 --> 00:26:02,025
may seem a little unusual,

465
00:26:02,025 --> 00:26:04,749
but they've been gradual, thoughtful investments

466
00:26:04,749 --> 00:26:06,251
put to something that I love.

467
00:26:06,251 --> 00:26:07,793
I'd rather spend money on figure skating

468
00:26:07,793 --> 00:26:08,674
than almost anything else.

469
00:26:10,847 --> 00:26:15,694
So I'm lucky enough to have the means and disposable income

470
00:26:15,694 --> 00:26:18,979
to put towards skating, especially

471
00:26:18,979 --> 00:26:20,321
as I don't have kids.

472
00:26:20,321 --> 00:26:22,925
But that's not true of all skaters or all gamers.

473
00:26:24,064 --> 00:26:26,466
Here's a friend that I skate with on Facebook posting

474
00:26:26,466 --> 00:26:29,709
about her decision not to go to nationals this year

475
00:26:29,709 --> 00:26:31,390
because her husband has lost her job

476
00:26:31,390 --> 00:26:34,372
and they need to budget and save.

477
00:26:34,372 --> 00:26:37,395
And she's saving, but she's putting the money goes

478
00:26:37,395 --> 00:26:39,876
to the mortgage first and then health care.

479
00:26:39,876 --> 00:26:42,258
And then she's saving for her nephew's wedding.

480
00:26:42,258 --> 00:26:44,380
But she's still finding enough money in the budget

481
00:26:44,380 --> 00:26:48,843
to skate and take lessons and do the base case.

482
00:26:48,843 --> 00:26:50,465
And then several other people are chiming in

483
00:26:50,465 --> 00:26:51,766
about their decision making.

484
00:26:52,360 --> 00:26:55,745
again deciding it was too expensive to go to nationals.

485
00:26:57,773 --> 00:27:01,794
The point here is that even avid fans

486
00:27:01,794 --> 00:27:04,575
are making rational, thoughtful decisions

487
00:27:04,575 --> 00:27:06,876
about how they're spending.

488
00:27:06,876 --> 00:27:09,196
Now, not every skater or gamer is

489
00:27:09,196 --> 00:27:12,397
making their spending decisions totally rationally

490
00:27:12,397 --> 00:27:13,097
and within their budget.

491
00:27:13,097 --> 00:27:18,938
There's always a spectrum of human behavior in any group,

492
00:27:18,938 --> 00:27:20,459
and there's always going to be some people who

493
00:27:20,459 --> 00:27:25,320
are trying to fill unmet emotional needs

494
00:27:25,320 --> 00:27:26,480
in unhealthy ways.

495
00:27:27,308 --> 00:27:30,231
But we don't blame department stores

496
00:27:30,231 --> 00:27:35,757
for the occasional compulsive shopper.

497
00:27:35,757 --> 00:27:37,899
And we shouldn't blame either figure skating or games

498
00:27:37,899 --> 00:27:39,641
for the occasional compulsive spender.

499
00:27:39,641 --> 00:27:41,182
And it's not just figure skating,

500
00:27:41,182 --> 00:27:42,904
and it's not just games.

501
00:27:42,904 --> 00:27:45,306
Other industries have similar dynamics.

502
00:27:45,306 --> 00:27:46,628
For example, the music industry.

503
00:27:48,148 --> 00:27:51,189
So if you start with a base of radio, which

504
00:27:51,189 --> 00:27:56,911
is a really mass audience, and streaming, and piracy,

505
00:27:56,911 --> 00:27:59,911
most artists are getting very little money

506
00:27:59,911 --> 00:28:03,152
from these sources.

507
00:28:03,152 --> 00:28:07,513
