00:31:01,810 --> 00:31:06,954
The people in the pro buy 10 times on average and spend $570.

561
00:31:06,954 --> 00:31:07,875
And that's just their spend within GameStop.

562
00:31:07,875 --> 00:31:11,518
They're probably spending on Steam and other places.

563
00:31:11,518 --> 00:31:12,399
Now the number, the breakout between

564
00:31:21,043 --> 00:31:26,826
Basic and pro on power up members is not a public number, but you can make a guess that it's got to be

565
00:31:26,826 --> 00:31:32,849
you know less than 10% of the GameStop audience and somewhere in the 40 to 50 percent range of

566
00:31:32,849 --> 00:31:33,309
total revenue

567
00:31:36,197 --> 00:31:39,918
So if this kind of distribution and this kind of setup

568
00:31:39,918 --> 00:31:44,100
is totally normal, why are we so uncomfortable with big spenders

569
00:31:44,100 --> 00:31:45,760
in free-to-play games?

570
00:31:45,760 --> 00:31:48,841
So uncomfortable that we quickly jump to mental illness

571
00:31:48,841 --> 00:31:52,062
and bad behavior on the game developer's part to explain it.

572
00:31:52,062 --> 00:31:52,943
So I think there's several reasons.

573
00:31:52,943 --> 00:31:53,283
One is data.

574
00:31:53,283 --> 00:31:55,023
Before free-to-play, we really didn't

575
00:31:55,023 --> 00:31:55,804
know how much people were spending.

576
00:32:03,862 --> 00:32:06,705
It was scattered across multiple sources,

577
00:32:06,705 --> 00:32:09,047
and those sources were generally retailers

578
00:32:09,047 --> 00:32:11,129
and platform holders.

579
00:32:11,129 --> 00:32:15,212
Until recently, I doubt that the retailers themselves knew.

580
00:32:15,212 --> 00:32:18,094
I worked in data analysis and marketing

581
00:32:18,094 --> 00:32:21,037
for several retail companies before we started Congregate.

582
00:32:21,993 --> 00:32:25,935
And at that time, we knew almost everything

583
00:32:25,935 --> 00:32:28,916
about customers who were buying through catalogs and web.

584
00:32:28,916 --> 00:32:32,117
But if we wanted any data from the store,

585
00:32:32,117 --> 00:32:34,578
it was always just anonymous transaction data.

586
00:32:34,578 --> 00:32:36,719
And there was no way to figure out who

587
00:32:36,719 --> 00:32:38,940
was purchasing again and again.

588
00:32:38,940 --> 00:32:40,201
An individual store manager might

589
00:32:40,201 --> 00:32:42,342
know who their big customers were

590
00:32:42,342 --> 00:32:45,363
and what they were spending on average.

591
00:32:45,363 --> 00:32:48,024
But it took loyalty programs, which really took off

592
00:32:48,024 --> 00:32:48,905
in the last 10 years or so.

593
00:32:49,726 --> 00:32:51,907
for people at the retail level to really understand

594
00:32:51,907 --> 00:32:54,449
and collect this kind of data.

595
00:32:54,449 --> 00:32:56,411
And even once they had it,

596
00:32:56,411 --> 00:32:59,553
they were probably reasonably comfortable with it,

597
00:32:59,553 --> 00:33:02,756
because this kind of concentration is normal

598
00:33:02,756 --> 00:33:04,057
regardless of what you sell.

599
00:33:04,057 --> 00:33:08,040
I have a funny story about Larry Ellison

600
00:33:08,040 --> 00:33:09,001
from a previous company

601
00:33:09,001 --> 00:33:10,482
that I probably shouldn't tell publicly,

602
00:33:10,482 --> 00:33:14,946
but if you ever catch me nodding at a podium,

603
00:33:14,946 --> 00:33:15,706
I will tell you what it is.

604
00:33:18,004 --> 00:33:23,452
So reason two is that spend is more concentrated,

605
00:33:23,452 --> 00:33:25,095
and we should be honest about that.

606
00:33:27,980 --> 00:33:30,442
It's more concentrated, and the biggest spenders

607
00:33:30,442 --> 00:33:31,323
are spending more.

608
00:33:31,323 --> 00:33:34,405
So this table shows off the dynamics

609
00:33:34,405 --> 00:33:38,269
of mobile and web markets, starting with a base case

610
00:33:38,269 --> 00:33:39,770
of a paid mobile app.

611
00:33:39,770 --> 00:33:43,533
These numbers are all made up, so don't read too closely

612
00:33:43,533 --> 00:33:43,793
into them.

613
00:33:43,793 --> 00:33:46,175
But I have enough data that I feel

614
00:33:46,175 --> 00:33:48,156
like these are pretty plausible as sort of above median cases,

615
00:33:48,156 --> 00:33:50,538
but way below actual real successes.

616
00:33:58,313 --> 00:34:02,094
In the current mobile market, it's really hard to get much of anyone to buy a game.

617
00:34:02,094 --> 00:34:04,395
There's just too much free content.

618
00:34:04,395 --> 00:34:08,557
When you go free, installs can explode, but conversion goes down

619
00:34:08,557 --> 00:34:11,298
and lives in a relatively narrow range.

620
00:34:11,298 --> 00:34:16,200
So what ends up mattering is whether players keep playing

621
00:34:16,200 --> 00:34:19,662
and keep spending and drive the average amount spent up.

622
00:34:19,662 --> 00:34:22,423
And that's why free-to-play is generating more revenue than paid.

623
00:34:22,943 --> 00:34:25,587
It's not because more people are getting into your game

624
00:34:25,587 --> 00:34:27,790
and having a chance to convert.

625
00:34:27,790 --> 00:34:30,034
Generally, you're going to have fewer buyers

626
00:34:30,034 --> 00:34:32,878
than you would have otherwise.

627
00:34:32,878 --> 00:34:35,722
But I think people think that that's what the dynamic is,

628
00:34:35,722 --> 00:34:38,205
that you're getting more people in who might buy.

629
00:34:40,469 --> 00:34:43,149
The total number of people buying is almost certainly going down

630
00:34:43,149 --> 00:34:47,930
because the more casually interested are not going to pay unless they have to.

631
00:34:47,930 --> 00:34:54,052
The reason that total revenue is up is because the most invested players

632
00:34:54,052 --> 00:34:58,593
who in a paid world spent the same as everyone else

633
00:34:58,593 --> 00:35:00,753
now have their spend uncapped.

634
00:35:00,753 --> 00:35:04,194
So some people who would have spent before enjoy the game for free

635
00:35:04,194 --> 00:35:07,415
and the most invested spend much more than they would have.

636
00:35:07,715 --> 00:35:10,224
essentially subsidizing a free experience for everybody else.

637
00:35:14,420 --> 00:35:18,121
Reason three is that we don't value digital games very highly.

638
00:35:18,121 --> 00:35:22,602
So I've put together a chart, again, with some good numbers

639
00:35:22,602 --> 00:35:26,524
from MPD and some really, really shitty numbers

640
00:35:26,524 --> 00:35:30,305
for paid PC games that are

641
00:35:30,305 --> 00:35:35,226
somewhat made up but somewhat plausible after talking to

642
00:35:35,226 --> 00:35:37,947
PC developers. So take it with a grain of salt.

643
00:35:37,947 --> 00:35:41,388
But the range of prices

644
00:35:41,388 --> 00:35:42,588
and sort of the...

645
00:35:43,236 --> 00:35:45,158
the general dynamics of total market size

646
00:35:45,158 --> 00:35:46,919
are probably pretty accurate.

647
00:35:46,919 --> 00:35:50,984
So console games have better graphics and more content

648
00:35:50,984 --> 00:35:54,808
to play through than most PC games or definitely

649
00:35:54,808 --> 00:35:56,049
most mobile games.

650
00:35:56,049 --> 00:35:59,793
But the average player only plays a small portion

651
00:35:59,793 --> 00:36:00,374
of that content.

652
00:36:00,374 --> 00:36:03,117
Completion rates on even the best games on console

653
00:36:03,117 --> 00:36:04,438
tend to be lower.

654
00:36:06,180 --> 00:36:07,041
to be around 30%, I believe.

655
00:36:07,041 --> 00:36:11,605
Well, some mobile and PC games are quite short.

656
00:36:11,605 --> 00:36:14,268
Monument Valley is pretty darn short, for example.

657
00:36:14,268 --> 00:36:17,190
The delta between play times is likely a lot less

658
00:36:17,190 --> 00:36:19,052
than the delta in price.

659
00:36:19,052 --> 00:36:23,836
Is a new console game really worth four to five times

660
00:36:23,836 --> 00:36:25,098
the average PC game, 20 to 25 times

661
00:36:25,098 --> 00:36:27,840
the average paid mobile game?

662
00:36:27,840 --> 00:36:30,082
I'm biased because I'm in that space,

663
00:36:30,082 --> 00:36:31,143
but I don't really think so.

664
00:36:32,165 --> 00:36:35,308
And the other thing is, again, these numbers are rough,

665
00:36:35,308 --> 00:36:38,631
but the market size of each of these genres,

666
00:36:38,631 --> 00:36:41,233
or not genres, platforms,

667
00:36:41,233 --> 00:36:42,514
marches roughly in step

668
00:36:42,514 --> 00:36:44,396
with the average sales price of a game.

669
00:36:44,396 --> 00:36:48,240
Though in theory, mobile and PC should be larger

670
00:36:48,240 --> 00:36:51,643
than console games because they're platforms

671
00:36:51,643 --> 00:36:53,024
that have much broader reach.

672
00:36:53,024 --> 00:36:54,626
Almost everybody has a computer,

673
00:36:54,626 --> 00:36:55,947
almost everybody has a smartphone.

674
00:36:57,545 --> 00:37:02,006
So why is price mattering more than the number of possible players?

675
00:37:02,006 --> 00:37:08,168
And that's because I believe demand for games is fundamentally inelastic.

676
00:37:08,168 --> 00:37:13,209
So what inelastic means is that when the price drops,

677
00:37:13,209 --> 00:37:18,490
the total amount sold increases, but not enough to account,

678
00:37:18,490 --> 00:37:22,051
to make up for the drop in price, so total revenue is lower.

679
00:37:23,397 --> 00:37:26,100
And I know you're thinking, OK, that

680
00:37:26,100 --> 00:37:27,261
doesn't make any sense at all.

681
00:37:27,261 --> 00:37:30,444
If that's true, why do PC game developers

682
00:37:30,444 --> 00:37:33,147
make so much more when they're part of Steam sales

683
00:37:33,147 --> 00:37:34,528
and Humble Bundle?

684
00:37:34,528 --> 00:37:37,090
Clearly, price is dropping and their revenue is going up.

685
00:37:37,090 --> 00:37:41,535
But when you think about it, that's what's going on

686
00:37:41,535 --> 00:37:44,558
is a sale and a special event.

687
00:37:45,554 --> 00:37:48,336
And they're getting a lot more promotion.

688
00:37:48,336 --> 00:37:52,859
If you drop the price without giving them

689
00:37:52,859 --> 00:37:56,942
a lot more attention and putting a perception in the mind

690
00:37:56,942 --> 00:37:59,264
of the player that they're getting this amazing limited

691
00:37:59,264 --> 00:38:03,366
time deal, the revenue for these games

692
00:38:03,366 --> 00:38:04,727
wouldn't go up at that same price.

693
00:38:04,727 --> 00:38:05,408
They would go down.

694
00:38:07,663 --> 00:38:11,285
Steam sales help draw more people into play PC games,

695
00:38:11,285 --> 00:38:14,606
which increases the sale for that category overall,

696
00:38:14,606 --> 00:38:17,688
and exposes consumers to a lot broader range

697
00:38:17,688 --> 00:38:19,328
of games and developers,

698
00:38:19,328 --> 00:38:21,509
which overall is really good for the industry.

699
00:38:21,509 --> 00:38:23,830
But it's probably mostly cannibalizing revenue

700
00:38:23,830 --> 00:38:25,191
that would otherwise have gone to console.

701
00:38:27,725 --> 00:38:32,489
So pricing studies have consistently shown that we make our decisions based on our perceived

702
00:38:32,489 --> 00:38:35,492
sense of value rather than price alone.

703
00:38:35,492 --> 00:38:40,256
And interestingly, price itself is a signal of value to most of us.

704
00:38:40,256 --> 00:38:46,021
So we assume that if the price being charged is higher, the item must be better.

705
00:38:46,021 --> 00:38:46,081
So

706
00:38:47,222 --> 00:38:51,123
If you see a higher priced wine, your default assumption is that it's better wine.

707
00:38:51,123 --> 00:38:55,405
You don't have really any way to know that, but the price is giving you that signal.

708
00:38:55,405 --> 00:39:03,508
If you go into a drugstore and you see a brand name like Aleve right next to the Walgreens Naproxen sodium,

709
00:39:04,385 --> 00:39:07,447
Those are exactly the same things, and yet people,

710
00:39:07,447 --> 00:39:10,750
and this includes me, have a tendency to go reach over

711
00:39:10,750 --> 00:39:13,653
and buy the Aleve because it must be better

712
00:39:13,653 --> 00:39:15,114
because it's more expensive.

713
00:39:15,114 --> 00:39:17,517
But it's really the same thing.

714
00:39:17,517 --> 00:39:19,718
So on mobile, we have anchored our perception

715
00:39:19,718 --> 00:39:21,540
of value really low.

716
00:39:21,540 --> 00:39:22,201
How much for them J's? $1,000.

717
00:39:22,201 --> 00:39:22,361
Sold.

718
00:39:22,361 --> 00:39:23,502
Yo, you gotta get some app.

719
00:39:23,502 --> 00:39:23,762
It's free.

720
00:39:23,762 --> 00:39:23,842
What?

721
00:39:23,842 --> 00:39:23,922
No, no!

722
00:39:35,154 --> 00:39:38,875
So we're all familiar with the terrible race to the bottom

723
00:39:38,875 --> 00:39:41,715
on paid game pricing that happened on iOS a few years back.

724
00:39:41,715 --> 00:39:44,816
There was no retail or platform who cared about

725
00:39:44,816 --> 00:39:48,497
the total sales to organize and control price wars,

726
00:39:48,497 --> 00:39:50,678
and the going price for games was quickly pushed down

727
00:39:50,678 --> 00:39:51,118
to 99 cents.

728
00:39:52,433 --> 00:39:58,058
Games that you can play for many hours are priced at or below a cup of coffee, or the

729
00:39:58,058 --> 00:40:01,242
cost of renting a movie that lasts 90 minutes.

730
00:40:01,242 --> 00:40:05,846
A few games can come in at higher prices, like Minecraft or Final Fantasy Tactics, when

731
00:40:05,846 --> 00:40:09,430
their value has been anchored high on another platform.

732
00:40:09,430 --> 00:40:12,593
And prices are slowly creeping up again.

733
00:40:12,593 --> 00:40:13,534
$3.99 is more common.

734
00:40:13,534 --> 00:40:14,235
$4.99 is more common.

735
00:40:15,067 --> 00:40:18,311
But for paid games to be viable for more developers,

736
00:40:18,311 --> 00:40:21,295
prices need to rise a lot, among other things,

737
00:40:21,295 --> 00:40:24,539
so that sale events can be more meaningful.

738
00:40:24,539 --> 00:40:26,181
A $0.99 drop may be 50% on $1.99 game,

739
00:40:26,181 --> 00:40:30,287
but it's not going to get a lot of people excited.

740
00:40:32,853 --> 00:40:36,394
So that's why free-to-play is so strong in the mobile market.

741
00:40:36,394 --> 00:40:38,715
Free-to-play games set their own value.

742
00:40:38,715 --> 00:40:40,335
In a free-to-play game, nobody can

743
00:40:40,335 --> 00:40:43,056
sell a good that's useful except you, which makes

744
00:40:43,056 --> 00:40:44,216
your game a little monopoly.

745
00:40:44,216 --> 00:40:46,957
It's an insecure monopoly, though, because the player

746
00:40:46,957 --> 00:40:48,337
can leave at any time.

747
00:40:48,337 --> 00:40:51,438
And if you piss them off by pricing things

748
00:40:51,438 --> 00:40:54,099
in weird and aggressive ways, they are likely to leave.

749
00:40:55,063 --> 00:40:59,587
There's no point price shopping packages of gold between games

750
00:40:59,587 --> 00:41:03,430
or the value of any kind of premium currency.

751
00:41:03,430 --> 00:41:05,631
The other game's items have no meaning in the game

752
00:41:05,631 --> 00:41:06,352
that you're playing.

753
00:41:06,352 --> 00:41:09,154
The more compelling and engaging the game,

754
00:41:09,154 --> 00:41:12,596
the more that players care about their status and progress,

755
00:41:12,596 --> 00:41:15,959
and the higher the value of the goods in the game

756
00:41:15,959 --> 00:41:18,921
become to the player, and the higher you can set your prices.

