00:41:20,893 --> 00:41:24,536
Which comes to the next reason that I think

758
00:41:24,536 --> 00:41:27,118
is affecting our perception of big spenders, which is that we

759
00:41:27,118 --> 00:41:28,780
don't value virtual goods.

760
00:41:28,780 --> 00:41:35,066
Our brains easily pin value on physical objects.

761
00:41:35,066 --> 00:41:37,108
Part of the reason console games have been able to continue

762
00:41:37,108 --> 00:41:40,551
to anchor their value high relative to digital versions

763
00:41:40,551 --> 00:41:41,692
is that disk.

764
00:41:41,692 --> 00:41:44,034
But that disk has been a tiny percentage

765
00:41:44,034 --> 00:41:46,956
of the cost of selling a console game for a very long time.

766
00:41:47,504 --> 00:41:50,071
It's the development, it's the retail share,

767
00:41:50,071 --> 00:41:50,753
it's the marketing.

768
00:41:50,753 --> 00:41:54,483
That's what's driving the cost up on just about everything.

769
00:41:56,297 --> 00:41:59,219
But even out of context, physical goods

770
00:41:59,219 --> 00:42:02,182
are always perceived as having value.

771
00:42:02,182 --> 00:42:04,343
But out of context of playing a game,

772
00:42:04,343 --> 00:42:06,145
virtual items have no meaning.

773
00:42:06,145 --> 00:42:08,187
They're incredibly abstract.

774
00:42:08,187 --> 00:42:10,389
And therefore, it's almost impossible for us

775
00:42:10,389 --> 00:42:12,891
to value something that we've never interacted with

776
00:42:12,891 --> 00:42:13,411
and never imagined.

777
00:42:13,411 --> 00:42:16,754
A physical good, we always assume

778
00:42:16,754 --> 00:42:20,137
it has a value because it had a cost to produce.

779
00:42:22,189 --> 00:42:25,892
So I think this is a large part of the success of Skylanders,

780
00:42:25,892 --> 00:42:29,476
for example, is that it bridges that gap between physical

781
00:42:29,476 --> 00:42:30,897
and virtual value.

782
00:42:30,897 --> 00:42:33,699
So a parent can go into a store and buy something

783
00:42:33,699 --> 00:42:36,902
that looks like something that they understand

784
00:42:36,902 --> 00:42:39,444
and give it to their child, who then converts it

785
00:42:39,444 --> 00:42:42,647
into a virtual item that has a lot more meaning to them.

786
00:42:45,750 --> 00:42:49,391
So another example is that spending $5,000 to $10,000

787
00:42:49,391 --> 00:42:54,174
on a specialized PC gaming rig that improves your skill

788
00:42:54,174 --> 00:42:57,896
and your competitiveness in a highly competitive game

789
00:42:57,896 --> 00:43:01,657
like League of Legends can easily cost $5,000 to $10,000.

790
00:43:01,657 --> 00:43:04,439
And it's fundamentally the same as spending $5,000 to $10,000

791
00:43:04,439 --> 00:43:04,479
on.

792
00:43:07,220 --> 00:43:10,600
skills and other things in a virtual game

793
00:43:10,600 --> 00:43:12,961
that would improve your competitiveness.

794
00:43:12,961 --> 00:43:14,721
But I bet you all find it a lot easier

795
00:43:14,721 --> 00:43:16,962
to contemplate and accept.

796
00:43:16,962 --> 00:43:19,062
If you walked into this room,

797
00:43:19,062 --> 00:43:20,842
you're much more likely to say, wow,

798
00:43:20,842 --> 00:43:23,583
than what were you thinking.

799
00:43:23,583 --> 00:43:29,604
But if the same person had spent that same money in game,

800
00:43:29,604 --> 00:43:31,084
you would be a little bit more concerned.

801
00:43:33,382 --> 00:43:35,663
For the person who's spending in game,

802
00:43:35,663 --> 00:43:40,445
these items have context and they have equal value.

803
00:43:40,445 --> 00:43:43,426
And just because you haven't experienced it

804
00:43:43,426 --> 00:43:44,107
doesn't make it less valid.

805
00:43:44,107 --> 00:43:48,989
So reason five is that I don't think we value games

806
00:43:48,989 --> 00:43:50,670
equally with other hobbies.

807
00:43:50,670 --> 00:43:55,332
Here's a lovely anti-game and slightly misogynistic quote

808
00:43:55,332 --> 00:43:57,553
from Ray Bradbury along that topic.

809
00:43:57,553 --> 00:44:01,254
And we don't value it not only with other hobbies

810
00:44:01,254 --> 00:44:02,995
or even other forms of entertainment.

811
00:44:03,841 --> 00:44:06,503
A few weeks ago, I was looking for a comprehensive history

812
00:44:06,503 --> 00:44:08,865
of games going back to ancient times.

813
00:44:08,865 --> 00:44:11,247
And I was surprised to find that one does not

814
00:44:11,247 --> 00:44:12,708
appear to have been written.

815
00:44:12,708 --> 00:44:15,030
Most universities have entire departments

816
00:44:15,030 --> 00:44:17,972
devoted to studying literature, film, and theater

817
00:44:17,972 --> 00:44:19,934
with virtually nothing about games.

818
00:44:19,934 --> 00:44:24,057
But we've been playing games back to thousands of years BC

819
00:44:24,057 --> 00:44:28,700
and playing and spending just as much time on them.

820
00:44:28,700 --> 00:44:32,363
And yet, we don't give them any credence

821
00:44:32,363 --> 00:44:33,304
in an intellectual way.

822
00:44:34,456 --> 00:44:39,019
Games are a waste of time, games are for kids, games aren't art.

823
00:44:39,019 --> 00:44:43,243
All of those things are sort of this sort of backbeat of culture.

824
00:44:44,412 --> 00:44:48,654
It's not hard for me to talk about my obsession with figure skating with non-skaters.

825
00:44:48,654 --> 00:44:53,495
People generally think that it's kind of quirky and charming, that I care about something

826
00:44:53,495 --> 00:44:56,396
that is a little strange.

827
00:44:56,396 --> 00:45:00,998
Caring about sports, even unusual sports where you're wearing sequins and makeup and play

828
00:45:00,998 --> 00:45:03,679
music is broadly accepted.

829
00:45:03,679 --> 00:45:07,840
But if it were a game that I was spending that much money on, I think I'd be more defensive,

830
00:45:07,840 --> 00:45:08,941
especially with non-gamers.

831
00:45:11,611 --> 00:45:16,434
The bias against games is so insidious that even within the industry, we've internalized

832
00:45:16,434 --> 00:45:20,476
enough that we question someone with means spending tens of thousands of dollars on a

833
00:45:20,476 --> 00:45:25,480
game, especially when you combine it with the low value we place on mobile and PC games

834
00:45:25,480 --> 00:45:27,561
and especially virtual goods.

835
00:45:27,561 --> 00:45:32,104
And so people jump to explanations like mental illness or evil games manipulating players.

836
00:45:33,024 --> 00:45:37,389
when the real explanation is that they are rational, wealthy people

837
00:45:37,389 --> 00:45:41,634
who are dedicated fans of a particular game and investing in their progress in it.

838
00:45:43,669 --> 00:45:44,830
So please don't call them whales.

839
00:45:44,830 --> 00:45:47,172
Call them hobbyists, call them super fans,

840
00:45:47,172 --> 00:45:48,073
call them something else.

841
00:45:48,073 --> 00:45:52,977
To call them whales is to dehumanize them.

842
00:45:52,977 --> 00:45:55,539
To talk of catching them suggests

843
00:45:55,539 --> 00:45:57,600
that they're blundering into your net

844
00:45:57,600 --> 00:46:00,443
or somebody else's net, rather than choosing

845
00:46:00,443 --> 00:46:03,305
to spend their time and money in a game.

846
00:46:03,305 --> 00:46:06,608
And if we as developers don't respect our players

847
00:46:06,608 --> 00:46:08,750
and the value that we create, who will?

848
00:46:12,703 --> 00:46:13,144
Thank you.

