00:48:47,674 --> 00:48:50,276
then every time you pull it,

888
00:48:50,276 --> 00:48:51,777
you're getting something that you value.

889
00:48:51,777 --> 00:48:54,339
So you should be feeling like,

890
00:48:54,339 --> 00:48:56,821
I got a good deal with this gotcha pull,

891
00:48:56,821 --> 00:48:58,202
even if I didn't get what I wanted.

892
00:48:58,202 --> 00:49:01,724
I think that sort of framework

893
00:49:01,724 --> 00:49:04,687
of how we think about designing free-to-play.

894
00:49:05,367 --> 00:49:08,467
is actually part of sort of the humanized idea

895
00:49:08,467 --> 00:49:10,728
of spenders and spending.

896
00:49:10,728 --> 00:49:14,068
That if we're thinking about everybody

897
00:49:14,068 --> 00:49:16,989
as sort of rational and thoughtful,

898
00:49:16,989 --> 00:49:18,369
then we should be thinking about

899
00:49:18,369 --> 00:49:21,150
how they feel immediately about purchasing

900
00:49:21,150 --> 00:49:25,711
and doing it in a way where it feels right every time.

901
00:49:25,711 --> 00:49:27,411
I'm not saying that that's exactly

902
00:49:27,411 --> 00:49:29,291
what's happening in every game,

903
00:49:29,291 --> 00:49:32,252
but for somebody to keep spending again and again and again,

904
00:49:32,252 --> 00:49:34,492
they must be feeling that they're getting a good value.

905
00:49:37,794 --> 00:49:39,755
What about variable ratio reinforcement?

906
00:49:39,755 --> 00:49:41,997
That's a hook that does keep people going,

907
00:49:41,997 --> 00:49:44,459
because it's a compelling feature that's

